6.1 Motivating principles
In this chapter we will explain how the di’¼Ćerential geometry we have discussed in previous chapters is related to physics. We will start by reviewing some physical principles that were important in the discovery of GR. Compared to the discussion of previous chapters, the material of this section is going to appear rather imprecise but we will see that it leads quite naturally to the idea that we should describe physics using a Lorentzian manifold.
We will use ŌĆ£SpacetimeŌĆØ (with a capital S) to refer to the (vague) physics notion of ŌĆ£the stage on which physics takes placeŌĆØ, to distinguish it from ŌĆ£spacetimeŌĆØ, which weŌĆÖve de’¼üned to mean a Lorentzian manifold.
